															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/cyclopian" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1990708); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1990708&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610205196" alt="Cyclopian" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1990708)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/cyclopian" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1990708); return false;" >Cyclopian</a></span> <span class="odate time_1449424903 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">06 Dec 2015 18:01</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2418413">
									

<p>This is pretty awesome, though I'm biased because I love real-world mythology, Sarkicism, and the CotBG. Meta's other Sarkic stuff has gotten me into Finnish myths, this has piqued a previously-unknown interest in Chinese myths. The artwork (and the in-universe justification for it) is also awesome. An easy +1.</p>
<p>I was initially a bit weirded out by the use of &quot;cogs&quot; in the third poem, considering that it was presumably written in Hittite cuneiform which I doubt has an actual sign that translates to &quot;cog&quot;, but then I realized that the Foundation has probably translated quite a few Mekhanite documents from that area and time period, and so in-universe has probably picked up on the meanings of unique Mekhanite cuneiform signs used to represent anachronistic machinery. Then I realized that it didn't matter, as I am most certainly overthinking things as well as being unnecessarily nitpicky.</p>

							</div>

								
					
